#end
:touch
$
$Pretty kewl, eh?
$
When you immediately exit a game, and
try to play it again, ZZT will load up
a game with the same FILENAME as the NAME
of the game you just played. A FILENAME
and a NAME are not the same thing. The
NAME of a ZZT game is stored into the
game's data, near the beginning, and
appears at the upper-right when you
load up a world. Though the second half
of the Encyclopedia has a certain
filename, its NAME is NEWWORLD. So when
you exit, it actually loaded up the game
NEWWORLD.ZZT. To set up this engine,
do the following steps:
$
$1) Make a world.
$2) Make another world.
$3) Make sure the name of the first world
$is the filename of the other. There
$are 2 ways to do this:
$
a) Save the game again as the name you
want. Delete the original copy.
Rename it back to the old filename.
It will have a different name, but
keep the filename.
b) Open the world in a text file and
rename it, keeping sure it is opened
as binary and the length of the name
is stored as the first byte in that
string.
$
I hope this wasn't too confusing... it's
really cool if you get it.
$
#end

